Watch Reform Moments | Manmohan Singh presents budget 1991

In July 1991, India kicked off a series of reforms to unleash its economy from the stifling rigidity of the socialist era. Manmohan Singh, the then finance minister, ended his budget speech of 1991–1992 with a quote from French novelist Victor Hugo: "No power on earth can stop an idea whose time has come."

The speech set the stage for the cleanest declared break from the past that India has seen on the economic front—both in years prior and since.
link_name: Reform Moments | Manmohan Singh presents budget 1991

Thanks for your response to our CityScapes photo contest. Here are the much-awaited results:
First Prize: @Aditya Bhadra
Congratulations! You win some great Satya Paul designerwear

And because we got some great photos and we thought they needed to be acknowledged, here are three photographers whose photos won the critic's choice award:
Rahul Wishard
Here's why we liked your photo: Rahul has captured the megacity from a vantage point, with good selection of the right wide-angle lens.
Abhimanyu Singh 
Here's why we liked your photo: Abhimanyu has captured a very light moment; some times ordinary-looking situations can make extraordinary and interesting communicating visuals.
Faiz Ullah.
Here's why we liked your photo: A perfectly timed shot, which made for an eye-catching picture. 
Congratulations, Rahul, Abhimanyu and Faiz!!! You all win some great Mint merchandise.
Do mail in your postal addresses to livemint.com@gmail.com at the earliest, so that we may ship your prizes to you. 
Check out our CityScapes album (http://www.facebook.com/media/set/?set=a.263947556988660.75630.170844986298918&type=1) for the winning photographs!!

Participate in the Mint-FB Photo contest and win some awesome Mint merchandise!!!

Theme: CITY SCAPES

Capture the essence of a city in a single frame. Every city has its own character, lent both by the architecture as well as the people, all you need to do is look through the lens a bit differently. 

Capture a city's mood, its people, its fixtures, its life... And it can be any city. 
Tell a story! 




HOW TO PARTICIPATE:
1. Select one/two picture(s) that YOU have shot and upload it on to the City Scapes event's page on FB (https://www.facebook.com/event.php?eid=246512568738279)

2. You can add your pictures by first clicking on "I'm Attending" (at the top-right corner of the page). This will allow you to add your photos on the event wall (at the bottom of the events page). Click on "Photo" and then "Upload a Photo".

3. Give a caption stating where the picture was shot, and what it is meant to depict.

4. Showcase your work, share your picture, and get your friends to "like" your picture. ('Coz the more the number of Likes, the bigger the chance of you winning!)

5. And spread the word. You never know, maybe there was a part of your city you didn't know and someone else did! So, go on, invite all your friends :-)


RULES and JUDGEMENT CRITERIA:
1. Do Not upload a picture that has been shot by any one else or is from any Web search.
2. You can upload a maximum of TWO photographs. If there are more photographs from the same person, just the first two will be considered.
3. Captions are mandatory. Pictures without captions will not be considered for prizes.
4. Photographs with the maximum number of "likes" will win some awesome Mint merchandise.
5. The winning photographs will be displayed as part of Mint's permanent picture gallery right here on Facebook.
